# pg -- "process grep": show running processes whose lines match a pattern,
# while always keeping the `ps` header row so the columns stay readable.
#
# What it does: captures `ps aux` (all processes, all users), prints the first
# line (the column header: USER PID %CPU ... COMMAND), then prints only the
# lines matching the pattern you pass as the first argument. Unlike a plain
# `ps aux | grep foo`, the header is preserved and you don't get the grep
# command itself cluttering the results (it ran before the search file existed).
#
# How to run it:
#   pg <pattern>        e.g.  pg sshd        pg python        pg root
# (No shebang; run via `sh pg <pattern>` or make it executable.)
#
# Prerequisites: ps, egrep (both standard).

# Build a unique temp filename. $$ is this shell's process ID so concurrent
# runs don't collide; the leading dot makes it hidden in /tmp.
tmpfile=/tmp/.grep.$$
# Create/empty that file ('>' alone truncates it to zero length).
>$tmpfile

# Snapshot all processes into the temp file.
#   ps aux : a = other users' processes, u = user-oriented columns,
#            x = include processes with no controlling terminal.
ps aux > $tmpfile
# Print line 1 only: the column header.
head -1 $tmpfile
# Print every line matching the user's pattern ($1). egrep = grep -E.
egrep $1 $tmpfile

# Clean up the temp file.
rm $tmpfile
